<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/03/28/intesa-sanpaolo-posts-steep-fourth-quarter-loss/" data-title="Intesa Sanpaolo Posts Steep Fourth-Quarter Loss" data-description="The surprising loss of 5.19 billion euros, or about $7.12 billion, was seen as another move by a European bank to clean up its balance sheet ahead of an asset review later this year.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">LONDON â The Italian bank Intesa Sanpaolo said Friday that it posted a large loss in the fourth quarter on charges for poorly performing loans and an accounting write-down.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The surprising loss of 5.19 billion euros, or about $7.12 billion, was seen as another move by a European bank to clean up its balance sheet ahead of an asset review of the euro zone&#8217;s largest banks by regulators later this year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Intesa,Â Italyâs second-largest lender by assets, also unveiled an updated business plan that includes the creation of a âbad bankâ to house and dispose of soured and nonperforming assets. It is one of the first Italian lenders to create a separate internal entity to do so, although several of its European peers have adopted the same approach.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">IntesaÂ also plans to close about 800 branches.</p>
<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/29/business/dbpix-intesa/dbpix-intesa-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/29/business/dbpix-intesa/dbpix-intesa-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/29/business/dbpix-intesa/dbpix-intesa-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002793695" width="592" height="381" alt="A branch of the Italian bank Intesa Sanpaolo in Milan."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="381"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A branch of the Italian bank Intesa Sanpaolo in Milan.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Stefano Rellandini/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The announcement of the loss comes as the <a title="More articles about European Central Bank" href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_central_bank/index.html?inline=nyt-org">European Central Bank</a> is expected to release in October the results of its review of how banks are valuing assets, such as real estate holdings, and whether they are setting aside enough money to cover potential losses in the future.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a title="More articles about Mario Draghi." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/d/mario_draghi/index.html?inline=nyt-per">Mario Draghi</a>, the central bankâs president, has warned that some banks may be found to be insolvent and forced out of business following the review.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Somewhat unexpectedly, Italian banks have taken the lead in baring their problems ahead of what the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_central_bank/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about European Central Bank">European Central Bank</a> promises will be a rigorous examination of bank assets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">UniCredit, based in Milan, disclosed a â¬15 billion loss for the fourth quarter on March 11, as it acknowledged that its holdings in Eastern Europe and Italy have lost value, and that many of the loans it has issued will never be repaid.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A day later, Monte dei Paschi di Siena, Italyâs third-largest bank and one of its most troubled, reported a â¬921 million loss for the fourth quarter as it recognized losses from problem loans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shares of both banks have risen in recent weeks as investors gained confidence that Italian lenders are putting their problems behind them. In addition, there is cautious optimism that Matteo Renzi, the Italian prime minister, who took office in February, will succeed in pushing through legislation that would streamline the countryâs moribund economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In one sign of returning confidence, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BLK&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about BlackRock Inc">BlackRock</a>, the worldâs largest investment company, bought a 5.75 percent stake last week in Monte dei Paschi, which until recently had been seen as a nearly hopeless case.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âSomething is changing in the mood of investors,â Giovanni Sabatini, general manager of the Italian Banking Association, said in an interview in Frankfurt this week. âEveryone is looking at 2014 as a turning point.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For Intesa, the fourth quarter included a â¬5.8 billion impairment on the goodwill of some of its businesses, including about â¬3.9 billion associated with its Banca dei Territori division. No impairment charges were taken in 2012.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Minus the impairment, the bank reported a profit of â¬578 million.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The accounting charge reflects Intesaâs conservative forecasts in the medium term, âdue to the monetary policy framework and the highly uncertain developments in the European economy in the coming years,â the bank said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The lender also set aside â¬3.1 billion to cover nonperforming loans, compared with â¬1.46 billion in the period a year earlier. The bank set aside â¬7.13 billion to cover bad loans in all of 2013.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The fourth-quarter results also included a â¬2.56 billion pretax gain on the revaluation of its stake in the Bank of Italy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Intesa said that operating income in the fourth quarter declined 12.2 percent to â¬3.94 billion, compared with the same period last year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Net interest incomeÂ â the difference between revenue earned on a bankâs assets versus expenses paid out on its liabilities â was down 6.6 percent, to â¬2.04 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For the full year, Intesa reported a net loss of â¬4.55 billion, compared with a profit of â¬1.61 billion in 2012.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Despite the loss, the bank said that it remained well capitalized and that it intended to pay a dividend in line with 2012. Intesa said that it would pay a dividend of â¬0.05 a share before tax, using about â¬822 million in cash from its reserves.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Jack Ewing contributed reporting from Frankfurt. </em></p>
